{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11375"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11375"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.14,0.6,0.17,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4020"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42064"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4020"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27036"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35886"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42064"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68 year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of left iliac fossa pain and fevers. He has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease. His medications include aspirin. On examination he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/70mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, temperature 38.9 \u00b0C and SpO2 97% on 2L oxygen via nasal specs. Abdominal examination shows that he is focally peritonitic in the left lower quadrant. A CT with intravenous contrast is performed, showing sigmoid diverticulitis with a 5.5cm pericolic abscess.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the preferred management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prolonged course of oral antibiotics","Initial trial of non-operative management with intravenous antibiotics alone","Intravenous antibiotics combined with percutaneous drainage","Laparoscopic peritoneal lavage and drainage","Laparotomy and Hartmann\u0027s procedure"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has complicated diverticulitis with a large diverticular abscess \u0026gt;5cm. The preferred management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous antibiotics combined with percutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E where feasible and available. This involves imaging guidance to insert a catheter into the abscess cavity for source control, as an abscess of this size is unlikely to resolve with antibiotics alone. In a patient with a small abscess \u0026lt;4-5cm or pericolic extraluminal gas, then management involves an \u003Cstrong\u003Einitial trial of non-operative management with intravenous antibiotics alone\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic peritoneal lavage and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is limited to selected patients with generalised purulent peritonitis, however in patients who are critically ill or deteriorate, then \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparotomy and Hartmann\u0027s procedure \u003C/strong\u003Eis required to resect the affected segment and perform an end colostomy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFinally, the management of acute uncomplicated diverticulitis was previously a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecourse of oral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E, however recent evidence has found no change in outcomes. Now the recommendation is for patients with uncomplicated diverticulitis who are immunocompetent without systemic inflammation, to have no antibiotics and early follow up. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with a large pericolic abscess \u003E5cm should be treated with intravenous antibiotics and percutaneous drainage where possible"],"references":["Sartelli M, Weber DG, Kluger Y, Ansaloni L, Coccolini F, Abu-Zidan F et al. 2020 update of the WSES guidelines for the management of acute colonic diverticulitis in the emergency setting. World J Emerg Surg. 2020;15(1):32. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32381121/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27036"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11375"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27036"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-29T21:38:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T18:47:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4020"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42064"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self